# Agent-Readable Content (ARC) Rules

> THIS: Rules for writing documentation that AI agents can actually read.
> Based on Stanford's "Lost in the Middle" research (Liu et al., 2023).

## The Problem You're Solving

LLMs have a U-shaped attention curve:
- First ~500 tokens: HIGH attention
- Middle content: LOW attention (the "dead zone")
- Last ~500 tokens: HIGH attention

Content in the middle gets skimmed or ignored.

---

## Required Structure for All .md Files

### 1. HEADER BLOCK (First 150 words) — HIGH ATTENTION ZONE

Every markdown file MUST begin with:

```markdown
# Title
> One-sentence summary that can stand alone without context

## TL;DR
- Most important point (action or fact)
- Second most important point
- Third most important point

HERE: What problem this file addresses.
THIS: What this file contains.
```

WAIT: Do not bury critical information below this header block.
The header must be self-contained and answer: "What is this and why does it matter?"

### 2. BODY CONTENT — THE DEAD ZONE

Middle content will be retrieved on-demand, not always read in full.

Structure for survival:
- Use H2 headers every 300-500 words (retrieval chunk boundaries)
- Each section should be independently understandable
- No section should exceed 800 words without a subheader
- Place "KEEP:" annotations before non-obvious patterns

### 3. FOOTER BLOCK (Last 100 words) — HIGH ATTENTION ZONE

Every markdown file MUST end with:

```markdown
---

## Links

LINK: Related to [Other Doc](./path.md) — brief reason
LINK: Depends on [Dependency](./path.md) — what this provides
LINK: See also [Reference](./path.md) — when to use

## Metadata

- Tokens: ~XXXX (approximate)
- Last validated: YYYY-MM-DD
```

---

## Cognitive Code Annotations (CCA)

Use these prefixes to signal intent to agents:

| Prefix | Purpose | Example |
|--------|---------|---------|
| `HERE:` | Grounds attention | "HERE: This is the auth module." |
| `THIS:` | Explains behavior | "THIS: Converts dates to UTC." |
| `KEEP:` | Marks intentional patterns | "KEEP: Empty catch is intentional." |
| `WAIT:` | Pause before changes | "WAIT: Order is load-bearing." |
| `ASK:`  | Prompt verification | "ASK: Is the API still v1?" |
| `LINK:` | Explicit coupling | "LINK: Must match config.yaml:12" |

---

## Size Constraints

| Metric | Limit | Why |
|--------|-------|-----|
| File size | < 4000 tokens | Fits in single retrieval chunk |
| Header block | < 150 words | Survives truncation |
| Section length | < 800 words | Sub-chunk addressable |
| Sentence length | < 20 words | Reduces parsing errors |

WAIT: Files exceeding 4000 tokens should be split into logical sub-documents.
Large files get middle-truncated during retrieval.

---

## Anti-Patterns

### ❌ Critical info buried in middle

```markdown
# Guide
Some intro text...
... 2000 words of context ...
IMPORTANT: The API key must be rotated weekly.  ← LOST
... more content ...
```

### ✅ Critical info in header

```markdown
# Guide
> API key rotation is required weekly.

## TL;DR
- Rotate API keys every 7 days
- Use the /rotate endpoint
- Old keys expire after 24 hours

HERE: API key management procedures.
```

### ❌ Long sentences

```markdown
The system processes incoming requests by first validating the authentication 
token against the user database and then checking permissions before routing 
to the appropriate handler which may trigger additional middleware.
```

### ✅ Short sentences

```markdown
The system validates auth tokens first.
Then it checks permissions.
Finally it routes to the handler.
Middleware may trigger during routing.
```

---

## Validation Checklist

Before committing any .md file, verify:

- [ ] First 150 words contain self-sufficient summary
- [ ] TL;DR section exists with 2-4 bullet points
- [ ] No critical information in middle 50% of file
- [ ] File is under 4000 tokens (run `arc lint`)
- [ ] Footer contains LINK: references
- [ ] H2 headers appear every 300-500 words
- [ ] Sentences average under 20 words

---

## Integration with llms.txt

All documentation should be indexed in `/llms.txt`:

```markdown
# Project Name
> One-line description

## Core Documentation
- [Architecture](./docs/architecture.md): System overview
- [API Reference](./docs/api.md): Endpoints and auth

## Optional
- [Contributing](./CONTRIBUTING.md): Can skip if context-limited
```

Files in "Optional" section are skipped when context is constrained.

---

## When Writing New Documentation

1. Start with the TL;DR — write it FIRST
2. Expand each bullet into a section
3. Add CCA annotations (HERE:, THIS:, KEEP:, etc.)
4. Add LINK: references in footer
5. Run `arc lint` before committing
6. Update llms.txt if new file

KEEP: This order is intentional.
Starting with TL;DR forces clarity before expansion.
